"Should we be able to preserve it against the incumbent weight of Connecticut on the one side, and the co-operating pressure of New Jersey on the other?",0,0,0,0,0,0
These are questions that temerity alone will answer in the affirmative.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The public debt of the Union would be a further cause of collision between the separate States or confederacies.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The apportionment, in the first instance, and the progressive extinguishment afterward, would be alike productive of ill-humor and animosity.",0,0,0,0,0,0
How would it be possible to agree upon a rule of apportionment satisfactory to all?,0,0,0,0,0,0
There is scarcely any that can be proposed which is entirely free from real objections.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"These, as usual, would be exaggerated by the adverse interest of the parties.",0,0,0,0,0,0
