Do the persons who rave at this rate imagine that their art or their eloquence can impose any conceits or absurdities upon the people of America for infallible truths?,1,0,0,0,0,0
"If there should be an army to be made use of as the engine of despotism, what need of the militia?",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If there should be no army, whither would the militia, irritated by being called upon to undertake a distant and hopeless expedition, for the purpose of riveting the chains of slavery upon a part of their countrymen, direct their course, but to the seat of the tyrants, who had meditated so foolish as well as so wicked a project, to crush them in their imagined intrenchments of power, and to make them an example of the just vengeance of an abused and incensed people?",1,0,0,0,0,0
Is this the way in which usurpers stride to dominion over a numerous and enlightened nation?,0,0,0,0,0,0
Do they begin by exciting the detestation of the very instruments of their intended usurpations?,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Do they usually commence their career by wanton and disgustful acts of power, calculated to answer no end, but to draw upon themselves universal hatred and execration?",1,0,0,0,0,0
Are suppositions of this sort the sober admonitions of discerning patriots to a discerning people?,0,0,0,0,0,0
Or are they the inflammatory ravings of incendiaries or distempered enthusiasts?,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If we were even to suppose the national rulers actuated by the most ungovernable ambition, it is impossible to believe that they would employ such preposterous means to accomplish their designs.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"In times of insurrection, or invasion, it would be natural and proper that the militia of a neighboring State should be marched into another, to resist a common enemy, or to guard the republic against the violence of faction or sedition.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"This was frequently the case, in respect to the first object, in the course of the late war; and this mutual succor is, indeed, a principal end of our political association.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If the power of affording it be placed under the direction of the Union, there will be no danger of a supine and listless inattention to the dangers of a neighbor, till its near approach had superadded the incitements of self-preservation to the too feeble impulses of duty and sympathy.",1,0,0,0,0,0
