41 General View of the Powers Conferred by The Constitution For the Independent Journal.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Saturday, January 19, 1788 MADISON To the People of the State of New York: THE Constitution proposed by the convention may be considered under two general points of view.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The FIRST relates to the sum or quantity of power which it vests in the government, including the restraints imposed on the States.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The SECOND, to the particular structure of the government, and the distribution of this power among its several branches.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Under the FIRST view of the subject, two important questions arise: 1.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Whether any part of the powers transferred to the general government be unnecessary or improper?,0,0,0,0,0,0
Whether the entire mass of them be dangerous to the portion of jurisdiction left in the several States?,0,0,0,0,0,0
Is the aggregate power of the general government greater than ought to have been vested in it?,1,0,0,0,0,0
This is the FIRST question.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It cannot have escaped those who have attended with candor to the arguments employed against the extensive powers of the government, that the authors of them have very little considered how far these powers were necessary means of attaining a necessary end.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"They have chosen rather to dwell on the inconveniences which must be unavoidably blended with all political advantages; and on the possible abuses which must be incident to every power or trust, of which a beneficial use can be made.",0,0,0,0,0,0
This method of handling the subject cannot impose on the good sense of the people of America.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It may display the subtlety of the writer; it may open a boundless field for rhetoric and declamation; it may inflame the passions of the unthinking, and may confirm the prejudices of the misthinking: but cool and candid people will at once reflect, that the purest of human blessings must have a portion of alloy in them; that the choice must always be made, if not of the lesser evil, at least of the GREATER, not the PERFECT, good; and that in every political institution, a power to advance the public happiness involves a discretion which may be misapplied and abused.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"They will see, therefore, that in all cases where power is to be conferred, the point first to be decided is, whether such a power be necessary to the public good; as the next will be, in case of an affirmative decision, to guard as effectually as possible against a perversion of the power to the public detriment.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"That we may form a correct judgment on this subject, it will be proper to review the several powers conferred on the government of the Union; and that this may be the more conveniently done they may be reduced into different classes as they relate to the following different objects: 1.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Security against foreign danger; 2.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Regulation of the intercourse with foreign nations; 3.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Maintenance of harmony and proper intercourse among the States; 4.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Certain miscellaneous objects of general utility; 5.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Restraint of the States from certain injurious acts; 6.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Provisions for giving due efficacy to all these powers.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The powers falling within the FIRST class are those of declaring war and granting letters of marque; of providing armies and fleets; of regulating and calling forth the militia; of levying and borrowing money.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Security against foreign danger is one of the primitive objects of civil society.,0,0,0,0,0,0
It is an avowed and essential object of the American Union.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The powers requisite for attaining it must be effectually confided to the federal councils.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Is the power of declaring war necessary?,0,0,0,0,0,0
No man will answer this question in the negative.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It would be superfluous, therefore, to enter into a proof of the affirmative.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The existing Confederation establishes this power in the most ample form.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Is the power of raising armies and equipping fleets necessary?,0,0,0,0,0,0
This is involved in the foregoing power.,0,0,0,0,0,0
It is involved in the power of self-defense.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"But was it necessary to give an INDEFINITE POWER of raising TROOPS, as well as providing fleets; and of maintaining both in PEACE, as well as in WAR?",0,0,0,0,0,0
The answer to these questions has been too far anticipated in another place to admit an extensive discussion of them in this place.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The answer indeed seems to be so obvious and conclusive as scarcely to justify such a discussion in any place.,0,0,0,0,0,0
With what color of propriety could the force necessary for defense be limited by those who cannot limit the force of offense?,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If a federal Constitution could chain the ambition or set bounds to the exertions of all other nations, then indeed might it prudently chain the discretion of its own government, and set bounds to the exertions for its own safety.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"How could a readiness for war in time of peace be safely prohibited, unless we could prohibit, in like manner, the preparations and establishments of every hostile nation?",0,0,0,0,0,0
The means of security can only be regulated by the means and the danger of attack.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"They will, in fact, be ever determined by these rules, and by no others.",1,0,0,0,0,0
It is in vain to oppose constitutional barriers to the impulse of self-preservation.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is worse than in vain; because it plants in the Constitution itself necessary usurpations of power, every precedent of which is a germ of unnecessary and multiplied repetitions.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"If one nation maintains constantly a disciplined army, ready for the service of ambition or revenge, it obliges the most pacific nations who may be within the reach of its enterprises to take corresponding precautions.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The fifteenth century was the unhappy epoch of military establishments in the time of peace.,0,0,0,0,0,0
They were introduced by Charles VII.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"All Europe has followed, or been forced into, the example.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Had the example not been followed by other nations, all Europe must long ago have worn the chains of a universal monarch.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Were every nation except France now to disband its peace establishments, the same event might follow.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The veteran legions of Rome were an overmatch for the undisciplined valor of all other nations and rendered her the mistress of the world.,1,1,1,1,1,1
"Not the less true is it, that the liberties of Rome proved the final victim to her military triumphs; and that the liberties of Europe, as far as they ever existed, have, with few exceptions, been the price of her military establishments.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"A standing force, therefore, is a dangerous, at the same time that it may be a necessary, provision.",1,0,0,0,0,0
On the smallest scale it has its inconveniences.,1,0,0,0,0,0
On an extensive scale its consequences may be fatal.,0,0,0,0,0,0
On any scale it is an object of laudable circumspection and precaution.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"A wise nation will combine all these considerations; and, whilst it does not rashly preclude itself from any resource which may become essential to its safety, will exert all its prudence in diminishing both the necessity and the danger of resorting to one which may be inauspicious to its liberties.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The clearest marks of this prudence are stamped on the proposed Constitution.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The Union itself, which it cements and secures, destroys every pretext for a military establishment which could be dangerous.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"America united, with a handful of troops, or without a single soldier, exhibits a more forbidding posture to foreign ambition than America disunited, with a hundred thousand veterans ready for combat.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It was remarked, on a former occasion, that the want of this pretext had saved the liberties of one nation in Europe.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Being rendered by her insular situation and her maritime resources impregnable to the armies of her neighbors, the rulers of Great Britain have never been able, by real or artificial dangers, to cheat the public into an extensive peace establishment.",1,1,0,1,1,0
The distance of the United States from the powerful nations of the world gives them the same happy security.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"A dangerous establishment can never be necessary or plausible, so long as they continue a united people.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"But let it never, for a moment, be forgotten that they are indebted for this advantage to the Union alone.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The moment of its dissolution will be the date of a new order of things.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The fears of the weaker, or the ambition of the stronger States, or Confederacies, will set the same example in the New, as Charles VII.",0,0,0,0,0,0
did in the Old World.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The example will be followed here from the same motives which produced universal imitation there.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Instead of deriving from our situation the precious advantage which Great Britain has derived from hers, the face of America will be but a copy of that of the continent of Europe.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It will present liberty everywhere crushed between standing armies and perpetual taxes.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The fortunes of disunited America will be even more disastrous than those of Europe.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The sources of evil in the latter are confined to her own limits.,1,1,1,1,1,1
"No superior powers of another quarter of the globe intrigue among her rival nations, inflame their mutual animosities, and render them the instruments of foreign ambition, jealousy, and revenge.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"In America the miseries springing from her internal jealousies, contentions, and wars, would form a part only of her lot.",1,1,0,1,1,0
