"The usurpations of the legislature might be so flagrant and so sudden, as to admit of no specious coloring.",0,0,0,0,0,0
A strong party among themselves might take side with the other branches.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The executive power might be in the hands of a peculiar favorite of the people.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In such a posture of things, the public decision might be less swayed by prepossessions in favor of the legislative party.",0,0,0,0,0,0
But still it could never be expected to turn on the true merits of the question.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It would inevitably be connected with the spirit of pre-existing parties, or of parties springing out of the question itself.",1,0,0,0,0,0
It would be connected with persons of distinguished character and extensive influence in the community.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It would be pronounced by the very men who had been agents in, or opponents of, the measures to which the decision would relate.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The PASSIONS, therefore, not the REASON, of the public would sit in judgment.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"But it is the reason, alone, of the public, that ought to control and regulate the government.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The passions ought to be controlled and regulated by the government.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"We found in the last paper, that mere declarations in the written constitution are not sufficient to restrain the several departments within their legal rights.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It appears in this, that occasional appeals to the people would be neither a proper nor an effectual provision for that purpose.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"How far the provisions of a different nature contained in the plan above quoted might be adequate, I do not examine.",0,0,0,0,0,0
